[{"location":"examples/concrete/README/#Code-to-generate-the-figures-below,-which-compare-different-approximations-for-the-effective-wavenumber-in-a-2D-concrete.-If-you-are-new-to-Julia,-please-open-the-ipynb-files-above,-which-show-how-to-run-the-code-in-your-browser-on-[JuliaBox](https://www.juliabox.com/).-1","page":"-","title":"Code to generate the figures below, which compare different approximations for the effective wavenumber in a 2D concrete. If you are new to Julia, please open the ipynb files above, which show how to run the code in your browser on JuliaBox.","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/concrete/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Code: concrete_species.ipynb (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D concrete) (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D concrete)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/concrete/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Code: concretespecies-largefreq.ipynb (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D concrete)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/concrete/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Code: concretespeciesvolfrac.ipynb (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D concrete)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/vary_two_species/README/#Vary-volume-fraction-of-the-two-species-1","page":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","title":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/vary_two_species/README/#","page":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","title":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","text":"Here we demonstrate how varying the volume fraction of two different species of particles changes the effective wave speed and attenuation.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/vary_two_species/README/#","page":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","title":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","text":"using EffectiveWaves\n\n# for fixed total volume fraction\nbackground = Medium(ρ=1.0,c = 1.0)\nωs = LinRange(0.01,1.0,60)\nvolfrac = 0.25\nr1 = 0.5\nr2 = 1.5\nN=5\nvols = LinRange(0.0,1.0,N)*volfrac\n\nks_arr = map(1:N) do i\n    sp1 = Specie(0.0, r1; volfrac=vols[i])\n    sp2 = Specie(Inf, r1; volfrac=volfrac-vols[i])\n    [ wavenumber_low_volfrac(ω, background, [sp1,sp2]) for ω in ωs]\nend\n\nspeeds = [ ωs ./ real(ks) for ks in ks_arr]\nattenuations = imag.(ks_arr)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/vary_two_species/README/#Plot-the-results-1","page":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","title":"Plot the results","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/vary_two_species/README/#","page":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","title":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","text":"labs = reshape( map(v -> \"void vol = $(Int(round(100*v)))%\",vols),1, length(vols));\np1 = plot(ωs, speeds,\n    labels=labs, ylabel=\"wave speed (m/s)\" ,xlabel=\"frequency\");\np2 = plot(ωs, attenuations,\n    labels=labs, xlabel=\"frequency\", ylabel=\"attenuation (1/m)\");\nplot(p1,p2,layout=(2,1))","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/vary_two_species/README/#","page":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","title":"Vary volume fraction of the two species","text":"(Image: vary_volfrac.png)","category":"page"},{"location":"base/#Base-1","page":"Base","title":"Base","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"base/#","page":"Base","title":"Base","text":"CurrentModule = EffectiveWaves","category":"page"},{"location":"base/#","page":"Base","title":"Base","text":"Pages = [\"base.md\"]","category":"page"},{"location":"base/#Material-and-particle-properties-1","page":"Base","title":"Material and particle properties","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"base/#","page":"Base","title":"Base","text":"Medium\nSpecie\nvolume_fraction\np_speed\nt_vectors\nZn\nmaximum_hankel_order","category":"page"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.Medium","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.Medium","text":"A homogenious background material.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.Specie","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.Specie","text":"A circular or spherical specie of particle with homogenious material properties.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.volume_fraction","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.volume_fraction","text":"Returns the volume fraction of the specie.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.p_speed","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.p_speed","text":"Returns pressure wave speed, when β is the adiabatic bulk modulus/\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.t_vectors","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.t_vectors","text":"A t_matrix in the form of a vector, because for now we only deal with diagonal T matrices.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.Zn","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.Zn","text":"Returns a ratio which gives the scattering strength of a particle\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.maximum_hankel_order","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.maximum_hankel_order","text":"Calculate the largest needed order for the hankel series.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#Types-of-waves-1","page":"Base","title":"Types of waves","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"base/#","page":"Base","title":"Base","text":"There are currently three main types used.","category":"page"},{"location":"base/#","page":"Base","title":"Base","text":"EffectiveWave\neffective_waves\nAverageWave\naverage_error\nx_mesh\nMatchWave\nmatch_error\nx_mesh_match","category":"page"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.EffectiveWave","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.EffectiveWave","text":"A type for the effective wave ansatz.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.effective_waves","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.effective_waves","text":"Calculates the effective wavenumbers and return Vector{EffectiveWave}.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.AverageWave","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.AverageWave","text":"A type for the ensemble average scattering coefficients. Here they are discretised in terms of the depth x of the halfspace\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.average_error","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.average_error","text":"Approximates the error in AverageWave.amplitudes due to the mesh AverageWave.x.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.x_mesh","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.x_mesh","text":"Returns x the mesh used to discretise the integral equations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.MatchWave","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.MatchWave","text":"A type for matched waves.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.match_error","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.match_error","text":"Calculates the difference between the match of MatchWave.effectivewaves and MatchWave.averagewave. This can be used as a proxi for convergence. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.x_mesh_match","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.x_mesh_match","text":"Returns (x,L), where x[L:end] is the mesh used to match with wave_effs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#Effective-wavenumbers-1","page":"Base","title":"Effective wavenumbers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"base/#","page":"Base","title":"Base","text":"wavenumbers\nwavenumber_low_volfrac\neffective_medium","category":"page"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.wavenumbers","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.wavenumbers","text":"Returns all the transmitted effective wavenumbers\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.wavenumber_low_volfrac","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.wavenumber_low_volfrac","text":"Explicit formula for one effective wavenumber based on a low particle volume fraction expasion.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.effective_medium","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.effective_medium","text":"the effective low frequency bulk modulus and density of a material filled with particles\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#Reflection-coefficients-1","page":"Base","title":"Reflection coefficients","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"base/#","page":"Base","title":"Base","text":"reflection_coefficient\nreflection_coefficient_low_volfrac\nreflection_coefficient_halfspace\ntransmission_angle","category":"page"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.reflection_coefficient","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.reflection_coefficient","text":"Calculates the reflection coefficient from each wave in waves and then sums the results.\n\n\n\n\n\nThe average reflection coefficient\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.reflection_coefficient_low_volfrac","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.reflection_coefficient_low_volfrac","text":"An explicit formula for the refleciton coefficient based on a low particle volume fraction.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.reflection_coefficient_halfspace","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.reflection_coefficient_halfspace","text":"the reflection from a homogenious halfspace, which is also the low frequency reflection from a particulate material when using the effective_medium.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"base/#EffectiveWaves.transmission_angle","page":"Base","title":"EffectiveWaves.transmission_angle","text":"calculate effective transmission angle θeff. We restrict -pi/2 < Re θeff < pi/2\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"examples/emulsion/README/#Code-to-generate-the-figures-below,-which-compare-different-approximations-for-the-effective-wavenumber-in-a-2D-emulsion.-If-you-are-new-to-Julia,-please-open-the-ipynb-files-above,-which-show-how-to-run-the-code-in-your-browser-on-[JuliaBox](https://www.juliabox.com/).-1","page":"-","title":"Code to generate the figures below, which compare different approximations for the effective wavenumber in a 2D emulsion. If you are new to Julia, please open the ipynb files above, which show how to run the code in your browser on JuliaBox.","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/emulsion/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Code: fluid_species.ipynb (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D emulsion) (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D emulsion)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/emulsion/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Code: fluidspecieslarge-freq.ipynb (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D emulsion)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/emulsion/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Code: fluidspeciesvolfrac.ipynb (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D emulsion)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/compare_two/README/#Code-to-generate-the-figures-below,-which-are-presented-in-the-paper-?.-The-figures-compare-different-approximations-for-the-effective-wavenumber-in-a-2D-concrete.-1","page":"-","title":"Code to generate the figures below, which are presented in the paper ?. The figures compare different approximations for the effective wavenumber in a 2D concrete.","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/compare_two/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"(Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D concrete) (Image: Compare effective wavenumber for 2D concrete)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/many_wavenumbers/README/#The-many-effective-wavenumbers-1","page":"The many effective wavenumbers","title":"The many effective wavenumbers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/many_wavenumbers/README/#","page":"The many effective wavenumbers","title":"The many effective wavenumbers","text":"using EffectiveWaves\n\nmedium = Medium(ρ=1.0, c=1.0)\n\nspecies = [\n    Specie(ρ=0.2, r=1.0, c=0.2, volfrac=0.25)\n];\n\nω = 0.6; # For one each angular frequency ω there are a multitude of effective wavenumbers.\nnum_wavenumbers = 8; # calculate the 8 least attenuating effective wavenumbers\n\n# often more wavenumbers a returned then asked for.\nk_effs = wavenumbers(ω, medium, species; num_wavenumbers=num_wavenumbers)\n\nusing Plots\nscatter(k_effs, lab=\"Effective wavenumbers\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/many_wavenumbers/README/#","page":"The many effective wavenumbers","title":"The many effective wavenumbers","text":"(Image: Many effective wavenumbers)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/many_wavenumbers/README/#","page":"The many effective wavenumbers","title":"The many effective wavenumbers","text":"We can calculate the resulting effective field (ensemble average field) from each of these effective wavenumbers by choosing an arbitrary wave amplitude of 1 for each wave.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/many_wavenumbers/README/#","page":"The many effective wavenumbers","title":"The many effective wavenumbers","text":"# with \"extinction_rescalse=false\" the amplitude will default to 1.\nwaves = [EffectiveWave(ω, k_eff, medium, species; extinction_rescale=false) for k_eff in k_effs]\n\n# choose the mesh the size of the lowest attenuating effective wavenumber\nx = range(0.; length=100, stop=2pi/abs(k_effs[1]))\n\nplot(x,waves[1], xlabel = \"x\", hankel_indexes = 0:1)\nplot!(x,waves[2], hankel_indexes = 0:1)\nplot!(x,waves[3], hankel_indexes = 0:1)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/many_wavenumbers/README/#","page":"The many effective wavenumbers","title":"The many effective wavenumbers","text":"(Image: Many effective wavenumbers)","category":"page"},{"location":"#EffectiveWaves.jl-Documentation-1","page":"Home","title":"EffectiveWaves.jl Documentation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"A Julia package for calculating, processing and plotting waves travelling in heterogeneous materials. The focus is on calculating the ensemble averaged waves, i.e. the statistical moments, of the waves. You can run Julia on JuliaBox in your browser without installation.","category":"page"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"At present, the packages calculates effective wavenumbers, wave transimission and wave reflection from random particulate materials, see arXiv preprint for some details on the mathematics, or these notes for the formulas.","category":"page"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"The package can deal with any volume fraction and frequency range.","category":"page"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"note: Note\nFirst install Julia v1.0.0 or later, then run in the Julia REPL:using Pkg\nPkg.add EffectiveWavesAlternatively, use the Julia package manager. From the Julia REPL, type ] to enter the Pkg REPL mode and then runpkg> add EffectiveWaves","category":"page"},{"location":"#Quick-introduction-1","page":"Home","title":"Quick introduction","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Here we calculate the effective wavenumbers for two species randomly (uniformly) distributed in Glycerol. We use only low volume fraction methods for simplicity.","category":"page"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"using EffectiveWaves\n#where: ρ = density, r = radius, c = wavespeed, and volfrac = volume fraction\n\nconst WaterDistilled= Medium(ρ=0.998*1000, c = 1496.0)\nconst Glycerol      = Medium(ρ=1.26*1000,  c = 1904.0)\n\nspecies = [\n    Specie(ρ=WaterDistilled.ρ,r=30.e-6, c=WaterDistilled.c, volfrac=0.1),\n    Specie(ρ=Inf, r=100.0e-6, c=2.0, volfrac=0.2)\n]\n# background medium\nbackground = Glycerol","category":"page"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"For a list of other materials go to examples/materials.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Calculate-effective-wavenumbers:-1","page":"Home","title":"Calculate effective wavenumbers:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"# angular frequencies\nωs = LinRange(0.01,1.0,60)*30.0e6\nks = wavenumber_low_volfrac(ωs, background, species)\n\nspeeds = ωs ./ real.(ks)\nattenuations = imag.(ks)","category":"page"},{"location":"#Plot-the-results-1","page":"Home","title":"Plot the results","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"using Plots\npyplot(linewidth=2.0)\n\np1 = plot(ωs, speeds, lab = \"\", ylabel = \"wave speed (m/s)\", xlabel = \"frequency\");\np2 = plot(ωs, attenuations, lab = \"\", ylabel = \"attenuation (1/m)\", xlabel = \"frequency\");\nplot(p1,p2, layout = (2,1))","category":"page"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"(Image: speed_and_atten.png)","category":"page"},{"location":"#Contents-1","page":"Home","title":"Contents","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Depth = 1","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/README/#[demo.jl](vary_two_species/README.md)-1","page":"-","title":"demo.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Shows how to choose two species, vary the volume fraction of them both, and plot the resulting sound speed and attenuation.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/README/#[Calculate-the-many-wavenumbers](many_wavenumbers/README.md)-1","page":"-","title":"Calculate the many wavenumbers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"For each angular frequency ω there are a multitude of effective wavenumbers.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/README/#[Demonstrate-the-matching-method](matched_method/README.md)-1","page":"-","title":"Demonstrate the matching method","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Compare the matched method with a purely numerical scheme. Both of these methods calculate the ensemble average wave in a particulate material.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/README/#[optimse_demo.jl](optimise_wavespeed/optimse_demo.jl)-1","page":"-","title":"optimse_demo.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/README/#","page":"-","title":"-","text":"Shows how to find the optimal species, given an objective function such as increase broadband attenuation.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#A-numerical-matching-method-1","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"Both of these methods calculate the ensemble average wave in a particulate material. To do so, we need to specify the geometry of the material, as this ultimately determines the fields. We choose the simplest case which is a halfspace x>0 filled with particles.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"using EffectiveWaves\n\n## choose a highly attenuating material\n    medium = Medium(ρ=1.0, c=1.0)\n    specie = Specie(ρ = 0.4, c = 0.3, r = 0.8, volfrac=0.2)\n\n    ω = 1.0\n    θin = 0.3 # angle made between incident wave direction and the material boundary\n\n    # calculate the 4 effective waves with the smallest attenuation\n    wave_effs = effective_waves(ω, medium, specie;\n          num_wavenumbers=5,\n          θin = θin,\n          extinction_rescale = false\n    )\n    # plot(wave_effs[1:5])\n    # savefig(\"wave_effs.png\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"(Image: Many effective wavenumbers)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"To determine the amplitude of these effective waves we used the newly developed matched method.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"    match_wave = MatchWave(ω, medium, specie;\n      θin = θin,\n      wave_effs = wave_effs[1:5],\n      max_size=80)\n\n    # the error of the match is used as a proxy to determine if the method converged. That is, the match_error is the difference between a sum of the effective waves and a discrete solution.\n    match_error(match_wave)\n\n    # plot(match_wave, ylim=(-0.1,0.3), xlab = \"x\", hankel_indexes=0:1)\n    # savefig(\"match_wave.png\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"(Image: The matched wave field)","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"We can compare this results against a purely numerical method, which requires a much larger mesh.","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"  average_wave = AverageWave(ω, medium, specie; θin = θin, max_size=700)\n\n  plot(average_wave, ylim=(-0.1,0.3), xlab = \"x\", hankel_indexes=0:1)\n  plot!(match_wave, seriestype=:line, match_region=false, hankel_indexes=0:1)\n  savefig(\"compare_match_wave.png\")","category":"page"},{"location":"examples/matched_method/README/#","page":"A numerical matching method","title":"A numerical matching method","text":"The two fields perfectly overlap, as the matched method is an exact method. Below the line is from the matched method, while the scatter points are from the purely numerical method. (Image: Compare matched and discrete field)","category":"page"}]
